ttacked lorries and been crushed in stampedes at food deliveries. America is trying to build a pier to receive bigger shipments of aid, but the project is still weeks away from completion and there are big questions around who will secure the pier and deliver the supplies.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;Fighting in much of Gaza has ebbed in recent weeks, but that has not eased hunger. The south has lots of needy people and not enough deliveries (usually fewer than 200 lorries a day). The north is less populous, but hard to reach and unsafe for many <small>;NGO</small>;s to operate in.</p>;<p data-component="paragraph" class="css-121tnhw e1tt35bk0">;For months Mr Netanyahu has refused to order the Israeli army to distribute aid in Gaza itself. But if Israel does not want <small>;UNRWA</small>; involved, and if other groups do not feel safe, Israel will have no choice. <span class="ufinish">;■</span>;</p>;</div>; https://www.economist.com/middle-east-and-africa/2024/04/03/what-israels-killing-of-aid-workers-means-for-gaza /content/61bvnmap0ufherlpd8rk55rru07mre0t Wed, 03 Apr 2024 15:45:42 GMT以色列
